{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17531098","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17531098"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:11:38+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:11:38+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14578"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14578"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.49,0.15,0.13,0.14,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7271"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95770"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7271","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7271"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14578"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78571"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"3358"},{"type":"tags","id":"4061"},{"type":"tags","id":"5630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17747"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17748"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32698"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32730"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/95770"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 68-year-old man is admitted to the Intensive Care Unit following a cardiac arrest with successful resuscitation and coronary artery stenting. He has a history of type 2 diabetes on metformin and dyslipidaemia on atorvastatin. He has been commenced on dual antiplatelets.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination the following day, he appears stable. His pulse rate is 85/min, mean arterial pressure 70 mmHg on low-dose noradrenaline, respiratory rate 18/min, SpO2 98% on 4 L/min oxygen via nasal cannula, and temperature 36.5\u00b0C. He is drowsy but rousable with no asterixis. His abdomen is soft and non-tender.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile liver function tests at admission were normal, investigations now reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlanine transferase: 3500 IU/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAspartate transferase: 3800 IU/L (5-40)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlkaline phosphatase: 120 IU/L (30-110)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBilirubin: 28 \u00b5mol/L (3-20)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EProthrombin time: 16 seconds (11-13)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EInternational normalised ratio: 1.4 (0.9-1.2)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management with regards to these investigations?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Continued monitoring","Fresh frozen plasma","Liver biopsy","N-acetylcysteine infusion","Liver transplant workup"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient had markedly elevated transaminases (\u0026gt;50 times the upper limit of normal) following a period of hypoperfusion due to cardiac arrest. This pattern, along with only mildly elevated alkaline phosphatase and bilirubin, is characteristic of ischaemic hepatitis, also known as shock liver or hypoxic hepatitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EContinued monitoring\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate management as the underlying cause (hepatic hypoperfusion) has already been addressed through successful coronary intervention and haemodynamic support. The liver has remarkable regenerative capacity, and function typically recovers spontaneously within days once adequate perfusion is restored. Serial monitoring of liver function tests and coagulation parameters is important to ensure improvement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFresh frozen plasma (FFP)\u003C/strong\u003E would not be indicated in this situation as the prothrombin time is mildly prolonged and the patient is not actively bleeding. FFP should not be routinely used in medical patients with coagulopathy, including those with liver impairment. Similarly, it should not be used routinely in critically ill patients with coagulopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver biopsy\u003C/strong\u003E carries risks and is unnecessary given the clinical picture. Alternative diagnoses can be excluded through less invasive means such as viral serology and imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EN-acetylcysteine infusion\u003C/strong\u003E has an established role in paracetamol-induced hepatotoxicity but has no proven benefit in ischaemic hepatitis. While it is sometimes used empirically in acute liver failure, there is insufficient evidence to support its routine use in this setting.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver transplant workup\u003C/strong\u003E would be premature and unnecessary. Ischaemic hepatitis typically has an excellent prognosis with supportive care alone, provided the underlying cause of hypoperfusion is addressed. Transplantation would only be considered in cases of irreversible liver failure, which is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ischaemic hepatitis typically presents with dramatic transaminase elevation (\u003E1000 IU/L) following a hypotensive episode.","Management of ischaemic hepatitis focuses on treating the underlying cause of hypoperfusion and supporting organ function.","Liver function typically recovers spontaneously within days if adequate perfusion is restored."],"references":["Waseem N, Chen PH. Hypoxic Hepatitis: A Review and Clinical Update. J Clin Transl Hepatol. 2016 Sep 28;4(3):263-268. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5075010","National Blood Authority (NBA) (2012). Patient Blood Management Guidelines:  Module 3 \u2013 Medical . NBA, Canberra, Australia","National Blood Authority (NBA) (2013). Patient Blood Management Guidelines:  Module 4 \u2013 Critical Care. NBA, Canberra, Australia"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78571"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14578"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"78571","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/78571"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-29T18:24:05+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-29T18:24:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7271"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"95770"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups",